Title: What does the "yield" keyword do in JavaScript?
Body: <p>What is the use of the <code>yield</code> keyword in JavaScript? What does it do?</p>
<p>For example, I'm trying to understand this code<sup><strong>1</strong></sup>:</p>
<pre><code>function* _get_child_candidates(distance, min_dist, max_dist) {
    if (this._leftchild && distance - max_dist &lt; this._median) {
        yield this._leftchild;
    }
    if (this._rightchild && distance + max_dist &gt;= this._median) {
        yield this._rightchild;
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>And this is the caller:</p>
<pre><code>const result = [];
const candidates = [this];
while (candidates.length) {
    const node = candidates.pop();
    const distance = node._get_dist(obj);
    if (distance &lt;= max_dist && distance &gt;= min_dist) {
        result.push(...node._values);
    }
    candidates.push(...node._get_child_candidates(distance, min_dist, max_dist));
}
return result;
</code></pre>
<p>What happens when the method <code>_get_child_candidates</code> is called?
Is an array returned? A single element? Is it called again? When will subsequent calls stop?</p>
