Title: How to catch multiple exceptions in one line? (in the catch block)
Body: <p>I know that I can do:</p>
<pre><code>try {
  // do something that may fail
} catch (err) {
  // do this if ANYTHING goes wrong
}
</code></pre>
<p>I can also do this:</p>
<pre><code>try {
  // do something that may fail
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof IDontLikeYouError) {
    // say please
  } else if (err instanceof YouAreTooShortError) {
    // stand on a ladder
  } else {
    throw err;
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p>But if I want to do the same thing for two different errors, the best I can think of right now is to do this:</p>
<pre><code>try {
  // do something that may fail
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof IDontLikeYouError) {
    // say please
  } else if (err instanceof YouAreBeingMeanError) {
    // say please
  } else {
    throw err;
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Is there any way that I can do something like this (since the action to take in both errors is to <code>say please</code>):</p>
<pre><code>try {
  // do something that may fail
} catch (IDontLikeYouError, YouAreBeingMeanError) {
  // say please
}
</code></pre>
<p>Now this really won't work, since JavaScript only allows a single catch parameter.</p>
<p>So, my effort to catch the two distinct errors doesn't exactly come through.</p>
<p>Is there a way to do this?</p>

