Title: Separation of business logic and data access in a Node.js app
Body: <p>I am writing a project in Node.js and I see that 80% of the code is in my ORM models. This code is confusing and, after a certain time, I cease to understand what is really happening.</p>
<p>Here is what bothers me:</p>
<ol>
<li>I find it ugly that my model level (which was supposed to be responsible only for the work with data from a database) is also sending email, calling APIs to other services, etc.</li>
<li>Also, I find it unacceptable to place business logic in the controller, because this way it becomes difficult to control. For example, in my application there are at least three ways to create new instances of <code>User</code>, but technically it should create them uniformly.</li>
<li>I do not always notice when the methods and properties of my models become non-deterministic and when they develop side effects.</li>
</ol>
<p>Here is a simple example. At first, the <code>User</code> model was like this:</p>
<pre><code>class User extends Model {
  getPresentName() {
    return this.name || 'Anonymous';
  }

  async activate() {
    this.status = 'activated';
    await this.save();
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Over time, it turned into this:</p>
<pre><code>class User extends Model {
  async getPresentName() {
    // property became non-deterministic in terms of database
    // data is taken from another service by API
    return (await remoteApi.requestUserName(this.uid)) || 'Anonymous';
  }

  async activate() {
    // method now has a side effect (send message to user)
    this.status = 'activated';
    await this.save();
    await sendMail('Your account is activated!', '…', [this.email]);
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p>What I want is to separate entities in my code:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Database level entities, i.e. database level logic: What kind of data does my application store?</strong></li>
<li><strong>Application level entities, i.e. business level logic: What does my application do?</strong></li>
</ol>
<p>What are the good practices to implement such an approach that can be applied in Node.js?</p>

